review:
If you are among the following, this Chromebook is not for you:

- The self-described "consultant," "analyst," or "I.T. professional" (with dubious or nonexistent credentials, like the guys who blog for Cnet or PCWorld), and describes software like MatLab or Adobe Creative Suite as "mainstream."

- Someone who is convinced he needs the latest Haswell dual-core 2 GHz CPU, at least 8 G of RAM, a terabyte of local storage, a discrete nVidia GPU, and a "Retina-quality display," even though he doesn't really understand what any of that means in practical terms.

- Someone who is either paranoid enough to think that Google is spying on him, or delusional enough to think his data is so monumentally important that Google would actively steal it, yet thinks nothing of leaving his Windows PC unattended and connected to broadband.

- A person who thinks Microsoft Word and word procesing are the same thing, or that spreadsheets are only possible with Excel.

- You think your current computer must be wholly self-contained, with all your data and applications on it at all times, even though that's hardly even possible these days.

If, on the other hand:

- You do not judge your self worth by the complexity or cost of the software on your computer;

- You do not feel it necessary to spend money and effort on hardware and software with "power" you will never need or use;

- You are more interested in doing things WITH your computer instead of TO it;

- You know that a $600 copy of Photoshop is not necessary to crop and enhance your birthday party snapshots;

- You want a computer that is ready to go, right out of the box, without need of additional software at extra expense;

- You want your data stored in such a way that if your computer fails, is lost, or is stolen, that your files are not lost with it;

Then a Chromebook might be perfect for you, and this one would be a good choice.

There are other Chromebooks to be had from Acer and HP that are not much different in price, and they appear to be good deals, too. I chose this one because I liked its keyboard the best and, since it needs no cooling fan, it operates in complete silence.

I have now bought two of these: one as a gift for a family member and then one for me. They were simple to set up and they work very well with very little effort. They are lightweight, inexpensive, and all the positive things you've read in other reviews here are true.

Update 16 Feb 2014:

Months in, and my enthusiasm for the Chrome OS platform and this Samsung Chromebook has not diminished. Still working flawlessly, and updates to the OS and apps offered for it have made it even better than when new. I'm using the Chrome Remote Desktop to access my PC and network at my job, and couldn't be happier with it. Google Drive, Docs, and Sheets have completely replaced MS Office for me, and I can share documents and data with my iPad and iPhone via iWork for iCloud. If you are looking for a new computer, seriously, look at a this or another Chromebook first.
